A Papilio troilus is a species of butterfly commonly known as the Spicebush Swallowtail.
It can be found in North America, mainly in the eastern regions.
The males and females differ in appearance, with the males having more prominent blue markings on their wings.
The wings of the Spicebush Swallowtail are large and broad, with a wingspan of 3 to 4 inches.
The upper side of its wings are a dark shade of black or brown with blue and green accents.
The underside of the wings are a lighter shade with orange, yellow, and blue markings.
These butterflies are often found in habitats near their host plant, the spicebush, and prefer areas with damp soil.
